<HEADLINE>
2006 REGULAR WAGE EXPECTED TO POSE GROWTH: DGBAS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei, Jan. 22 (CNA) 01/22/07  21:53:59 (By Elizabeth Hsu)
</P>
<P>
Regular salaries of local wage earners were assessed as showing
positive growth in 2006, the first gain in three years, the
Cabinet-level Directorate General of Budget, Accounting and
Statistics (DGBAS) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The forecast was based on statistics that showed regular wages
grew 0.66 percent in the first 11 months of 2006 while a 0.88
percent increase was recorded in terms of salaries including non-
regular wages in the same period, DGBAS officials said.
</P>
<P>
Huang Chien-chung, a DGBAS deputy department chief, said at a
news conference that the number of the people employed in the
industrial and service sectors totalled 6.087 million at the end
of November, marking an increase of 9,000 over the October level
and an increase of 95,000 year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
In November, a survey showed that workers or employees in these
sectors worked an average of 186.6 hours, which represented a 10
hour increase from October.
</P>
<P>
In terms of salary, the average salary was over NT$39,000
(US$1,187) in November, showing an annual growth of 0.9 percent,
Huang said, adding that the average salary for the 11-month
period stodd at NT$44,000, marking a 0.88 percent year-on-year
growth.
</P>
